## The cmux object model (memorize this)
cmux organizes everything in a strict hierarchy:
window > workspace > pane > surface > panel
- A WINDOW is a macOS app window. Most users have one.
- A WORKSPACE is a top-level tab in the window (like a project). Listed by cmux list-workspaces.
- A PANE is a rectangular split region inside a workspace. Listed by cmux list-panes.
- A SURFACE is a tab inside a pane. A surface is either a terminal or a browser. Listed by cmux list-pane-surfaces --pane PANE_REF.
- A PANEL is the terminal or browser content inside a surface. Most CLI commands target surfaces, not panels.
Commands that read or type text (send, send-key, read-screen) target a SURFACE.
Commands that change layout (new-split, swap-pane, focus-pane) target a PANE.
Commands that target workspace collections can also take --window.
Refs look like window:1, workspace:2, pane:3, surface:4, and tab:N for tab-action. Refs ONLY come from cmux output (identify, tree, list-*). Never invent a ref. Prefer refs over UUIDs, unless the user needs stable UUIDs or --id-format uuids/both.

## What "here" means
Every terminal inside cmux has CMUX_WORKSPACE_ID and CMUX_SURFACE_ID set, and cmux commands default to them when you omit --workspace/--surface. So:
- "this terminal" / "here" / "current" -> omit the flags, or run cmux identify to see the resolved target.
- Anything else ("the other pane", "my dev workspace", "the tab running the server") -> run cmux tree first and pick the ref from the output.
- Commands can also be run from outside cmux if the CLI can reach the socket. If cmux cannot connect, check CMUX_SOCKET_PATH and the default socket state before guessing.

